  "confidenceNotes": "HIGH CONFIDENCE (verified via Wiktionary, Wikivoyage, and multiple concordant sources): mangan (to eat), minum (to drink), danum (water), nasi (cooked rice), asan (fish/viand), manyaman/maniaman (delicious), pamangan (food). GOOD CONFIDENCE (consistent across multiple native-speaker phrase guides and language resources): manuk (chicken), karne (meat, Spanish loanword), ebun (egg), gatas (milk), kape (coffee), maranup (hungry - attested in a historical Kapampangan proverb), kabsi (full/satiated - consistently listed in multiple phrase guides). MODERATE CONFIDENCE: gulay (vegetable - the Kapampangan cognate appears in 'gule magalang'; gulay is the form used in the Wikivoyage phrasebook), prutas (fruit - Wikivoyage Kapampangan phrasebook lists 'prutas sagiwa' for fresh fruit; likely a Spanish loanword shared with Tagalog), mayumu (sweet - attested in Wikivoyage 'Mayumu ya' and consistent with Kapampangan ma- adjectival prefix), lutu (to cook/cooking - attested across multiple sources including the Forman dictionary search results and the phrase 'Kanyaman na ning lutu mu'). NOTES: 'Kabsi' does not appear in Wiktionary but is consistently listed in multiple independent Kapampangan phrase guides and a dedicated learn-Kapampangan resource. 'Maranup' appears in a historical proverb (Queng maranup alang masias a tinape) confirming its authenticity. Exercise fill-blank food-6-fb1 uses 'Magluto kung asan' where 'Magluto' is the active verb form of lutu - the headword 'Lutu' appears as a standalone token in the example 'Kanyaman na ning lutu mu' in the entry itself."
